  {
    "lesson_id": "042",
    "trigger_word": "provi",
    "title": "LESSON 42: ACTIVE PARTICIPLES",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Active participles describe the DOER of an",
          "action in different times. Three forms:",
          "",
          "-ANT- = doing now (present)",
          "legi → leganta = reading (now)",
          "parolanta = speaking (now)",
          "",
          "-INT- = having done (past)",
          "legi → leginta = having read",
          "parolinta = having spoken",
          "",
          "-ONT- = about to do (future)",
          "legi → legonta = about to read",
          "parolonta = about to speak",
          "",
          "La leganta viro... = The reading man...",
          "La leginta viro... = The man who read...",
          "La legonta viro... = The man about to read..."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvardek du"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "043",
    "trigger_word": "okazi",
    "title": "LESSON 43: THE 'EK-' PREFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The prefix EK- captures that exact moment",
          "something starts — a sudden kick into action.",
          "",
          "SUDDEN START OF ACTION:",
          "iri     → ekiri      = go → set off",
          "dormi   → ekdormi    = sleep → fall asleep",
          "kanti   → ekkanti    = sing → begin singing",
          "",
          "MORE EXAMPLES:",
          "ekplori  = burst into tears",
          "ekvidi   = catch sight of",
          "ekridi   = burst out laughing",
          "",
          "COMPARE:",
          "Li kuris. = He was running.",
          "Li ekkuris. = He broke into a run.",
          "",
          "EK- = the kick that starts everything!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvardek tri"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "044",
    "trigger_word": "historia fono",
    "title": "LESSON 44: THE 'PRA-' PREFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The prefix PRA- means \"ancient\" or \"great-\"",
          "(for generations). It reaches back in time.",
          "",
          "ANCESTRAL (stack PRA- for more generations):",
          "avo     → praavo     = grandpa → great-grandpa",
          "avino   → praavino   = grandma → great-grandma",
          "patro   → prapatro   = father → forefather",
          "prapraavo = great-great-grandfather",
          "",
          "ANCIENT:",
          "homo    → prahomo    = human → protohuman",
          "arbaro  → praarbaro  = forest → old-growth",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "Mia praavo venis el Francio.",
          "(My great-grandfather came from France.)",
          "",
          "PRA- reaches back through time!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvardek kvar"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "045",
    "trigger_word": "hipoteze",
    "title": "LESSON 45: PASSIVE PARTICIPLES",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Passive participles describe the RECEIVER",
          "of an action in different times:",
          "",
          "-AT- = being done (present)",
          "legi → legata = being read",
          "la legata libro = the book being read",
          "",
          "-IT- = done/completed (past)",
          "legi → legita = read/having been read",
          "la legita libro = the read book",
          "",
          "-OT- = about to be done (future)",
          "legi → legota = about to be read",
          "la legota libro = the book to be read",
          "",
          "ACTIVE VS PASSIVE:",
          "leganta viro = a reading man (he reads)",
          "legita libro = a read book (it was read)"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvardek kvin"
      }
    ]
  },
